<p><span> </span></p>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:366;s:16:"post_image_width";i:800;s:11:"post_visits";i:3;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:16;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:17;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:33;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:17;s:13:"post_virality";i:28;s:9:"blog_name";s:14:"Absolute Geeks";s:16:"blog_description";s:28:"Unleash The Tech Geek In You";s:8:"blog_url";s:24:"http://absolutegeeks.com";s:11:"blog_author";s:0:"";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:13:"absolutegeeks";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:34:"http://www.absolutegeeks.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:4:"tech";s:2:"id";i:268;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1401602040;}i:19;O:8:"stdClass":26:{s:7:"post_id";i:28703;s:8:"post_url";s:44:"http://tech-ticker.com/android-silver-nexus/";s:10:"post_title";s:30:"Android Silver: No More Nexus?";s:10:"post_image";s:0:"";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"Google is apparently shifting strategies a whole lot these days. After the reported news about Google dropping Google+ t...";s:7:"blog_id";s:11:"tech-ticker";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1398798960;s:12:"post_content";s:4137:"<p>Google is apparently shifting strategies a whole lot these days. After the reported news about Google <a title="Google+ Nearly Reaching The End" href="http://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/~tech-ticker.com/google-nearly-reaching-end/" target="_blank">dropping Google+</a> to the backside bin, here comes rumors talking about the Android Silver project. <strong>‘</strong><a href="http://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/~https://www.theinformation.com/Google-Takes-Aim-iPhone-Silver-Program" target="_blank"><span><span><strong>The Information’</strong> reports</span></span></a> that the current Nexus-branded handset line sporting Google’s unadulterated vision of the best Android user experience will be trashed, to be replaced by a set of high-end Silver phones. Google is said to be planning to spend heavily on promoting these upcoming devices and subsidizing the development and marketing costs for its hardware partners, willing to spend as much as $1 billion to get phone makers to jump aboard the new initiative.</p>
<p>Why Android Silver? Google will potentially gain tighter control over the software shipping on the selected phones. The promise is that the company will clean up third-party bloatware, ensure prompt and reliable software updates, and introduce a real standard and consistency to the user experience across Android Silver devices.</p>
<p>These new devices will be introduced to every manufacturer’s lineup. But they will definitely need a lot of convincing to adhere to the project. Nevertheless, some of them already offer Google Play Editions of their flagship phones. But… thinking of it again, Google Play Edition is rather close enough to Android Silver…</p>
<p>It does look like Google wants to try and regain control of its mobile platform. Google is definitely shifting hard towards Android. A better Android. Making it an even stronger brand than what it is currently. But what is particularly peculiar about this rumored strategy is the fact that Google will kind of be letting the middle-end Android market go adrift. Kind of weird when we look back at the Moto X and Moto G programs, launched less than a year ago.</p>
